eorem, and aspects of Kolmogorov-Arnold-Moser theory. He then explores chaotic orbits, exemplified in a restricted three-body problem, and describes the existence and importance of homoclinic points. This book is indispensable for mathematicians, physicists, and astronomers interested in the dynamics of few- and many-body systems and in fundamental ideas and methods for their analysis. After thirty years, Moser's lectures are still one of the best entrées to the fascinating worlds of order and chaos in dynamics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCelestial mechanics. 7aSCIENCE / Physics / Astrophysics.2bisacsh  aAccuracy and precision.  aAction-angle coordinates.  aAnalytic function.  aBounded variation.  aCalculation.  aChaos theory.  aCoefficient.  aCommutator.  aConstant term.  aContinuous embedding.  aContinuous function.  aCoordinate system.  aCountable set.  aDegrees of freedom (statistics).  aDegrees of freedom.  aDerivative.  aDeterminant.  aDifferentiable function.  aDifferential equation.  aDimension (vector space).  aDiscrete group.  aDivergent series.  aDivisor.  aDuffing equation.  aEigenfunction.  aEigenvalues and eigenvectors.  aElliptic orbit.  aEnergy level.  aEquation.  aErgodic theory.  aErgodicity.  aEuclidean space.  aEven and odd functions.  aExistence theorem.  aExistential quantification.  aFirst-order partial differential equation.  aForcing function (differential equations).  aFréchet derivative.  aGravitational constant.  aHamiltonian mechanics.  aHamiltonian system.  aHessian matrix.  aHeteroclinic orbit.  aHomoclinic orbit.  aHyperbolic partial differential equation.  aHyperbolic set.  aInitial value problem.  aInteger.  aIntegrable system.  aIntegration by parts.  aInvariant manifold.  aI